<DOC><DOCNO> AP890702-0048 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1729EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-02 0559</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0577</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Rain, High Wind Across Parts Of South, Into Ohio Valley</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Severe thunderstorms with damaging wind developed Sunday over thesouthern Plains, very heavy rain fell along parts of the Gulf ofMexico coast, and thunderstorms also broke out on the northernPlains and near the Great Lakes.   Record high temperatures were recorded in southwestern Texas. Bymidafternoon, Midland reached a record 108 degrees and San Angelohad tied its mark of 105.   In contrast, clouds kept temperatures in the chilly 50s and 60sacross the Pacific Northwest.   Thunderstorms produced wind gusts to between 60 and 70 mph atmore than a dozen locations in central Oklahoma during the morning.Siding was blown off a house at Enid and wind blew down utilitypoles in Lindsay, the National Weather Service said. Thunderstormsalso hit Kansas.   The combination of a low pressure area in the upper atmosphereand the remnants of Tropical Storm Allison produced a large area ofrain from the central Gulf Coast to the lower Ohio Valley.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. CDT included2.05 inches at Wichita, Kan., and 1.26 inches at Evansville, Ind.   Flash flood watches were posted for south-central andsoutheastern Kentucky, central and southeastern Tennessee andnorthern and western Alabama.   Thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain across the central GulfCoast states.   Along the Mississippi Gulf Coast, 5.22 inches of rain fell atBiloxi, and 3.94 inches fell at Gulfport in about three hours duringthe morning. Gulfport got 9.19 inches of rain between midnight and 1p.m. CDT.   Four inches of rain fell between midnight and noon CDT atCordova, Ala.   A thunderstorm produced a tornado that caused slight damage inMobile County, Ala., the weather service said. A tornado alsooccurred briefly at Long Beach, Miss., but no damage was reported.   Louisiana rivers continued to rise in the aftermath of recordrainfall from the remnants of Tropical Storm Allison, with scatteredstorms and showers replacing the unremitting rain of the previousfive days. One town got nearly 29 inches of rain in less than a week.   Intense thunderstorms moved across northeastern North Dakota andnorthern Minnesota during the morning. Hail the size of marbles fellat Cavalier, N.D., and wind gusted to 50 mph near Whitman, N.D.   Thunderstorms also developed over sections of northern Indianaand southwestern Lower Michigan, with a wind gust to 58 mph during athunderstorm at Muskegon, Mich.   Elsewhere, thunderstorms were scattered across much of Florida.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58degrees at Olympia and Tacoma, Wash., to 108 at Carlsbad, N.M.Sunday's low in the Lower 48 states was 26 at Truckee, Calif.   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom the central and eastern Gulf Coast to the upper Great Lakesregion, especially over the upper Ohio Valley and southernAppalachians. A few showers were forecast over the Pacific Northwest.   Highs only in the 60s and 70s were predicted in the PacificNorthwest and along most of the California coast; in the 70s overMaine and in the southern Appalachians; over 100 across parts ofColorado and Utah; between 100 and 115 from southwestern Texasacross New Mexico to the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90sacross most of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>